  <div class="hero">
    <span class="eyebrow">Food &amp; Nutrition</span>
    <h1>Best High-Protein Foods After 50<br /><em>(Simple. No Cooking Required.)</em></h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Hitting 120+ grams of protein a day sounds hard until you know which foods do the heavy lifting. Here's what actually works — no meal prep, no complicated recipes, no chef skills needed.</p>
    <p class="meta">SnapProtein · 8 min read</p>
  </div>

  <article class="article-wrap">
    <div class="quick-answer">
      <div class="qa-label">Short answer</div>
      <p><strong>The best high-protein foods for men over 50 are Greek yogurt, cottage cheese, eggs, canned tuna, rotisserie chicken, and whey protein.</strong> These six foods require minimal or no cooking, deliver 20–35 grams of protein per serving, and can be combined to hit your daily target without meal prep or complicated planning.</p>
    </div>

    <p class="lead">
      I'm 64 and I don't meal prep. I don't have hours to spend in the kitchen and I'm not interested in complicated recipes just to hit a protein number. What I found — and what most men over 50 find — is that a handful of simple, reliable foods do most of the work. You don't need variety. You need consistency.
    </p>

    <p>
      The goal is 0.7 to 1.0 grams of protein per pound of body weight, spread across three to four meals. For most men, that means hitting roughly 30 grams per meal. This list is organized around that target — real foods, real protein counts, and exactly how to use them without turning every meal into a project.
    </p>

    <p>
      You don't need 20 foods. You need 5–6 you'll actually eat consistently. That's the whole strategy.
    </p>

    <a href="/blog/protein-after-50/" class="related-post">
      <div>
        <div class="rp-label">Not sure what your target is?</div>
        <div class="rp-title">How Much Protein Do Men Over 50 Actually Need? →</div>
      </div>
      <span class="rp-arrow">→</span>
    </a>

    <h2>The Six Foods That Do Most of the Work</h2>

    <p>
      These aren't exotic superfoods. They're the everyday staples that consistently deliver high protein with low effort — and they happen to be some of the easiest high-protein foods for older adults to work into a daily routine. If these six are stocked regularly, hitting your daily protein target becomes a logistics problem — not a willpower problem.
    </p>

    <div class="food-card">
      <div class="food-header">
        <div class="food-name">Greek Yogurt</div>
        <div class="food-badge">17–20g per cup</div>
      </div>
      <div class="food-desc">
        The highest-protein, lowest-effort food in the dairy aisle. Plain, full-fat Greek yogurt delivers roughly 17–20 grams per cup with zero preparation. It also contains leucine — the amino acid most directly linked to muscle protein synthesis — making it particularly valuable for men over 50 dealing with anabolic resistance.
      </div>
      <div class="food-tip">Buy plain, not flavored — flavored versions are loaded with added sugar. Add fruit yourself if you need sweetness.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="food-card">
      <div class="food-header">
        <div class="food-name">Cottage Cheese</div>
        <div class="food-badge">25g per cup</div>
      </div>
      <div class="food-desc">
        Consistently underrated. One cup of cottage cheese delivers around 25 grams of high-quality protein, including casein — a slow-digesting protein that continues feeding muscle protein synthesis for several hours after eating. Eat it at dinner or before bed and it works while you sleep.
      </div>
      <div class="food-tip">Pairs well with fruit, crackers, or eaten straight. Takes about 30 seconds to serve.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="food-card">
      <div class="food-header">
        <div class="food-name">Eggs</div>
        <div class="food-badge">6g per egg</div>
      </div>
      <div class="food-desc">
        Eggs are the most complete protein source available — meaning they contain all nine essential amino acids in proportions your body can use efficiently. Three eggs plus one cup of Greek yogurt is a complete 38-gram protein breakfast. Hard-boil a batch on Sunday and you have portable protein ready all week with zero morning effort.
      </div>
      <div class="food-tip">Hard-boiled eggs keep refrigerated for up to one week. Batch cooking once removes the daily decision entirely.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="food-card">
      <div class="food-header">
        <div class="food-name">Canned Tuna</div>
        <div class="food-badge">25–30g per can</div>
      </div>
      <div class="food-desc">
        One 5-oz can of tuna delivers 25–30 grams of protein, costs under two dollars, requires no refrigeration before opening, and takes 60 seconds to prepare. It's the most efficient protein-per-dollar food on this list. Mix with a little olive oil and lemon, eat on crackers, or fork it straight from the can.
      </div>
      <div class="food-tip">Stock 10–15 cans at a time. When you're short on time or ideas, a can of tuna is always the answer.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="food-card">
      <div class="food-header">
        <div class="food-name">Rotisserie Chicken</div>
        <div class="food-badge">35–40g per breast</div>
      </div>
      <div class="food-desc">
        A full rotisserie chicken from any grocery store costs $7–10 and provides three to four high-protein meals with zero cooking. One breast delivers 35–40 grams of protein. Pull it apart, refrigerate what you don't eat immediately, and you have ready protein for two days. This is the single best time-to-protein ratio on the list.
      </div>
      <div class="food-tip">Pick one up weekly. It replaces cooking for multiple meals and costs less per gram of protein than almost anything else in the store.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="food-card">
      <div class="food-header">
        <div class="food-name">Whey Protein</div>
        <div class="food-badge">25g per scoop</div>
      </div>
      <div class="food-desc">
        Not a replacement for whole food — but an essential backup when meals fall short. One scoop of whey protein powder in water or milk delivers 25 grams of fast-absorbing protein in under two minutes. Particularly useful at breakfast (when whole-food protein tends to be lowest) and immediately after training.
      </div>
      <div class="food-tip">Look for a whey isolate or concentrate with minimal ingredients. If you're lactose sensitive, whey isolate is the lower-lactose option.</div>
    </div>

    <h2>How to Build a 30-Gram Meal Without Cooking</h2>

    <p>
      Knowing the foods is step one. Knowing how to combine them quickly is what makes the habit sustainable. These are real combinations that hit the 30-gram target with minimal effort.
    </p>

