    <h2>The Breakfast Problem (And How to Fix It)</h2>

    <p>
      Breakfast is where most men over 50 leave the most protein on the table. The typical American breakfast — cereal, toast, orange juice — delivers 8–12 grams of protein at best. The target is 30. That gap at the first meal of the day cascades through the whole day.
    </p>

    <p>
      The fix doesn't require cooking. It requires stocking the right things and combining them with intention. Greek yogurt plus two eggs — prepped the night before — is a complete 30-gram breakfast that takes about 90 seconds to assemble.
    </p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <p><strong>The one shift that changes everything:</strong> Replace your current breakfast with a 30-gram protein version for two weeks. Most men report noticeably better energy, reduced mid-morning hunger, and improved focus within the first week. The effect is that fast when you go from 10 grams to 30 at the first meal.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>What About Protein Supplements?</h2>

    <p>
      Whole food first — always. The foods listed above are more satiating, more complete nutritionally, and build better long-term habits than relying on shakes. But protein powder earns its place as a gap-filler, not a foundation.
    </p>

    <p>
      If you're consistently falling 20–30 grams short of your daily target despite eating well, one scoop of whey in the morning or after training closes the gap efficiently. The mistake is using shakes as a substitute for building a solid food foundation. Use them as backup — not as the plan.
    </p>

    <div class="author-note">
      <div class="author-icon">R</div>
